Subject Immortal Application~
Text
I would like to apply to become an immortal.  Now I understand that this
may be met with hesitancy as I\@m not exactly the most popular player on the
mud, but I feel that I could bring a lot to the staff.  I would like to
become an immortal because I feel that the mud desperately needs new
players.  From my own experience, as well as the experience of some people
that I\@ve spoke with in-game, it\@s the mud that makes them feel special that
they like to stick to.  For some people, it\@s the roleplay that makes them
feel special.  For others, it\@s the player base.  For a great deal of
people, however, it\@s when an immortal takes time to interact with them,
regardless of level.  It\@s what got me hooked, and kept me coming back, in
the form of a rather interesting conversation with my level 10 with Marlax.

I\@ve mudded off and on for somewhere around 6 years, starting my second
year in high school.  Avendar was my very first mud, and with a couple
slight exceptions, my only mud.  I took an afternoon off once to try out
Carrionfields, because people had mentioned it.  I died to someone right
away, and that was enough for me.  Also, I was an Immortal for a very short
time on a mud one of Avendar\@s former players started up, but that died
shortly after.  I love to roleplay.  It\@s why Jolinn still holds my soul,
despite how many times I\@ve tried to take it back.  I just can\@t get enough
of the wonderful environment Avendar offers for roleplaying.  However, in my
time at Avendar, I feel I\@ve only had a few successful characters.  What I
call a character successful means to me that when I log on that character,
and something happens to evoke an emotion in them, I can reciprocate that,
because when I made the character, I became the character.  Such characters
that I would consider successful by that standard would be Phaelis, Aesai,
Tylia and Aelisa.

The Temple of the Kei Atkuye

First, some background.  Ever since Girikha was awesome enough to run an
event for Aelisa, involving an ancient, buried temple of the Alatharya
beneath the sands of the desert, I\@ve been absolutely infatuated with the
area.  That, coupled with my particular fondness for Egyptian and Persian
archaeology, led me to design an area around those three themes.  I call the
area the Temple of the Kei Atkuye, which is translated to the High Chosen of
the Alatharya.  It is a temple set far south in the desert, to the west of
Ashta Harrud, although inaccessible by normal means, such as walking right
up to it.  My idea for the area is to make it a sort of expedition area, in
which once a party enters; they cannot escape through normal means, such as
Xiganath.  I intend on giving people who learned alatharyan as a language a
little boost through the area, so items such as the ring and others within
will have things written in alatharyan, which show up translated to that
person, much in the same way the writing on the door to the minarets shows
up. 

The temple is the primary meeting place for the leaders of the Alatharya,
called the Kei Atkuye, or the High Chosen.  It was within the temple that
they made the decision to construct the devices to imprison the gods,
although none of the devices were constructed within the temple, so as not
to draw any unnecessary divine attention to it.  This is why the temple was
preserved through the sundering, unlike the other temple.  While serving as
a meeting place, it is also their arcane sanctuary, where they would
research and study.  This is representative of the animated guardians that
protect the place from all, including other Chosen.

The area itself won\@t be announced, like others were via a note, but
rather through a global event.  A ring, the signet of the Kei Atkuye, is
dropped from a mob that is imm-possessed and difficult to slay, but after
doing so, will spawn only at certain times, such as midnight on a certain
ingame day.  When the ring is worn, it shows a vision of an arch set in the
middle of a desert to the wearer.  The ring cannot be dropped, so whoever
picks it up is stuck with it.  Also, it cannot be identified; giving a
message such as your divinatory magics cannot penetrate the ring.  When the
person wearing the ring reaches the arch in the wastes, it pulses, sending
them south to the crimson sands.  In the sands, people can come across the
buried arch by seeing its top, but only the ring can cause the arch to
reveal itself.  From there, the group of no more than 5 (I hate how players
zerg a new area, like what happened with the mines) can go through a 1-way
portal inside.  The entire area will consist of four parts.  There will be a
courtyard, then the grand hall with the rotunda, two towers accessible
through the hall, and then the arcane vault, which will be opened by
obtaining artifacts in the grand hall and in the two towers.

When players enter the portal, they are placed at a second arch, and in
front of them is the temple.  I want to give the feel that the entire area
was preserved in time, standing as it was before the Sundering.  The
exterior of the temple is a lush garden, set in a grand courtyard of pure
white stone.  There are three animated guardians that stand at three points
around a fountain set in the center of the courtyard.  Each guardian
represents two opposing elements of magic, earth and wind, water and fire,
spirit and void.  They will each use spells from both schools, as well as a
spell that combines both, such as the void-wreathed fire cast by the elder
templar.  As far as difficulty goes, I would say each should be a about as
hard as the top end leveling mobs, such as the Siyyad.  As each is slain, it
drops a piece of a stone disc that, when combined, provide a key to the
front door.  Once the disc is assembled, it will allow players to enter the
door into the great hall.

Once inside the door, players are greeted with a slew of mosaics
depicting the Chosen in all their arrogance.  Through a long, arching
hallway, they eventually enter the rotunda, a gigantic dome with a circular
stone inset in the floor.  The inset, called the Stone of Two Moons, can
only be opened by placing two moonstones within the seal, then defeating the
guardian, which will cause it to fall into a circular staircase.  To the
right and left of the rotunda is a pair of hallways that lead players to the
two towers.  The towers were constructed because the Alatharyans believed
that they would be able control the moons with them.  Thusly, the eastern
tower is the tower of Telianthis, and the western tower that of Nimiel.
Lesser guardians patrol each level of the towers, which are filled with
living spaces for the Kei Atkuye.  Once players reach the upper levels of
the tower, living spaces are replaced with mechanical devices and arcane
research designed to control each of the moons.  Standing guard over these
devices, as well as the two moonstones, are the Guardians of Telianthis and
Nimiel, powerful constructs crafted in the image of the Chosen themselves.
As far as difficulty goes for these, I would say they should be a good bit
tougher than the top end leveling mobs, though not as powerful as the srryn
elders.  Each would perform special abilities, calling upon their respective
moons for power.  Telianthis, being the brighter and smaller of the two,
would call upon the more beneficial aspects of the moon, such as healing.
Nimiel, being darker in nature, would result in more destructive purposes.

When the two moonstones are placed together in the Stone of Two Moons,
the Guardian will be summoned.  The guardian is a spectral creature, crafted
of pure magic, and survived through the Sundering because it does not exist
until someone tries to access the Arcane Vault.  When first summoned the
Spectral Guardian will not initiate combat, but instead stand there.  The
ring will then pulse for whoever is wearing it, and the Spectral Guardian
will turn to them and ask them what they seek from the Vault, whether it is
power, or knowledge.  Answering power will cause the Spectral Guardian to
use more martial attacks, special combat techniques that deal more physical
damage.  Answering knowledge will cause the Spectral Guardian instead to use
spells, calling upon combinations of the greater elements in the form of
dual-sphere spells.  Once the guardian is defeated, the Stone of Two Moons
will split in a spiral pattern, dropping into a stone stairwell down to the
Arcane Vault.

As players descend into the vault, the first room the encounter is the
council chamber, dominated by states of the Chosen as pillars, holding up a
dome on which a mosaic of the world is inlaid.  Beneath the dome is a great
circular table.  It was at this table that the Kei Atkuye laid out their
plans to steal the Quintessence.  At the head of the table, a skeleton of
one of the Chosen will still sit over the council.  Around the skeleton\@s
neck will be a necklace of tiny crystal beads that, when worn, gives a
person 100% in every language (maybe overpowered, but at least it\@s not
combat).  Descending below the council chamber will enter a small chamber
with two doors.  To the east, the door is marked with the symbol of
Telianthis, and to the west, Nimiel.  If the player answered knowledge, the
ring will pulse, and the door of Telianthis will open.  If power, then the
door of Nimiel will open.

Through the door of Telianthis lies a small library, filled with empty
shelves.  Set in the middle, on a stand, lies one thick tome.  Those who can
understand alatharyan, and those who wear the necklace from the corpse, can
read the tome which describes its use.  Holding the tome grants players 100%
scrolls.  Also, once every real life, a player may instruct the book to
create a scroll of any spell in the game, including greater ones.  The spell
is inscribed on the last page of the book, and then removed to the player\@s
inventory.  Through the door of Nimiel, lies an armor stand with two bracers
set upon it, one etched with Nimiel, one etched with Telianthis.  Wearing
the bracer etched with Nimiel will call forth an unremovable blade into the
player\@s main hand, granting a sword the player automatically gains 100%
with (if a swordmaster with higher percent, does not lower current percent).
Wearing the bracer etched with Telianthis will call into being an
unremovable shield that grants the player 100% shield block.  Entering
either room will cause the ring of the Kei Atkuye to shimmer, and draw
itself into the finger of the person wearing it.  This does two things.
First, it summons a portal which allows exit from the temple, and second, it
gives that person +1 to their max and current primary stat for their class.
This effect cannot happen more than once per character.  

I am, of course, fully open to criticism and suggestions on the area, as
well as any other questions you may have.

Thank you,
Aelisa
