As most of you probably know, a few weeks ago, I asked for a special bit
of IMM interaction with a character I had created.  Namely, I asked for her
to be permanantly deafened.  I recieved this after a couple days, and went
about writing a suitable background/description/extended description for
her.  Something I felt would do her justice.  While doing so, I began
thinking about how limiting being permanantly deafened truly is.  

Not so much in that a person cannot hear, which is what my character was
created around, but in the fact that deafness itself hardly does the
condition justice.  Needless to say, I apologize for allowing my interest in
her wane to the point that she was deleted by inactivity.  However, I do
have a suggestion that would pay hommage not only to her role, but allow for
people with similar disabilities in the future to roleplay their roles as
best they can.  I suggest that the way deafness works be changed.  

Currently, when a character is deafened, they are stripped of the ability to
see says, esays, tells, yells, and anything else having to do with sound
(barring the few area-wide echoes, such as eagles crying out in the
mountains, or hearing rustling in Morn).  This is fine, except that it takes
away from a rather large asset to any deaf person: animation.  I, like many
others, put actions into my esays, such as esay \@purses her lips, then
says\@...  Deafen takes away the esay completely, including any actions that
might have been included in the prefix.  What I propose is that instead of
eliminating the entire esay or say, instead blank out the actual part that
is said, replacing it with ...  Or something.  Tells would still be blanked
out, because one does not have a moving mouth with which to make reference,
same with yells.  This change would only affect says and esays, primarily
esay.  I consider it essential for any deaf character to be able to judge
from facial expressions, body language, and so forth how another character
might be feeling.  

Just a small suggestion, and again, I\@m sorry for allowing her to fall to
the wayside.  
-Kristen
~
